<styl>by <m2>By <m0>DAVID LYONS<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Staff Writer<ep>
   A Dade jury has awarded $79,000 to a hotel sales manager who was fired because she did not return to work as quickly as her bosses wanted after her child was delivered stillborn. <ep>
   Maria Chinea, 29, earned $30,000 a year coordinating U.S. sales from Miami for a Dominican hotel chain called Hotelero Naco Inc., which operates properties in Santo Domingo and Puerto Plata.<ep>
   When she told her employer she was pregnant, Chinea requested and received eight weeks of maternity leave. But after she lost the baby in April 1993, the hoteliers ordered her to return before the leave expired.<ep>
   ``You have to ask yourself, does this make sense?'' attorney Alice Warwick asked the jury.<ep>
   Defense lawyer Scott McNary argued that it made eminent sense. Chinea, he said, was uncommunicative after she lost the baby, and company executives received anonymous reports that she had been spotted at shopping malls, appearing quite healthy.<ep>
   During a trial before Circuit Judge Alan Postman this week, Chinea denied <m2><ql>
