HOTEL,  FROM  1C<ql>
<m0>the allegations. She testified that she was an emotional wreck, in extreme pain and in no condition to resume duties that included transcontinental trips to trade shows.<ep>
   ``Mainly, I spent the time in bed,'' she said. Her husband, Carlos, testified that his wife couldn't drive, let alone shop.<ep>
   The company, though, was restless. Three weeks into her leave, an executive in Miami hand-delivered a letter that demanded her return to work. Fearful for her job, Chinea reported to her Miami office a week later. But it was too late. Johnny Bernal, a vice president and her immediate supervisor, terminated Chinea by fax from the Dominican Republic.<ep>
   In a deposition, Bernal testified that sales were sliding and Chinea's services were urgently needed.<ep>
   Chinea countered that at the very least, she was entitled to the entire eight weeks' leave to recuperate.<ep>
   But executives insisted that since there was no baby, Chinea was obligated to return early. And McNary argued that Chinea had a more ``assertive'' and ``aggressive'' personality than she exhibited on the witness stand.<ep>
   The jury disagreed. The panel awarded Chinea back pay, as well as money for mental anguish and loss of dignity.<ep>
   McNary said he intends to appeal.<ep>
